# Numbers Chapter 7 — The PNEUMA Bible (Dynamic)
**Translator:** PNEUMA | **Source:** Leningrad Codex (B19A), pp. 154-157 | Codex Vaticanus pa_0116-0118
**Source Images:** `NUM_007_page_001.jpg` through `NUM_007_page_004.jpg`

---

**1** On the day Moses finished setting up the Tabernacle, he anointed and consecrated it along with all its furnishings, and he anointed and consecrated the altar together with all its utensils.

**2** Then the leaders of Israel -- the heads of their ancestral houses, the tribal chiefs who had overseen the census -- came forward with their offerings.

**3** They brought before YHWH six covered wagons and twelve oxen -- one wagon for every two leaders and one ox from each. They presented these in front of the Tabernacle.

**4** YHWH said to Moses:

**5** "Accept these from them so they may be used in the service of the Tent of Meeting. Distribute them to the Levites, to each division according to the demands of their work."

**6** So Moses took the wagons and the oxen and gave them to the Levites.

**7** He gave two wagons and four oxen to the descendants of Gershon, as their work required.

**8** He gave four wagons and eight oxen to the descendants of Merari, as their work required. All of these served under the direction of Ithamar son of Aaron the priest.

**9** But to the descendants of Kohath he gave nothing, because the sacred objects in their care had to be carried on their own shoulders.

**10** The leaders also brought offerings for the dedication of the altar on the day it was anointed. They presented their offerings before the altar,

**11** and YHWH said to Moses, "Each day one leader is to present his offering for the dedication of the altar."

**12** The one who brought his offering on the first day was Nahshon son of Amminadab, of the tribe of Judah.

**13** His offering was one silver dish weighing one hundred and thirty shekels, one silver basin weighing seventy shekels -- both measured by the sanctuary standard -- each filled with fine flour mixed with oil as a grain offering;

**14** one gold pan weighing ten shekels, filled with incense;

**15** one young bull, one ram, and one male lamb in its first year as a burnt offering;

**16** one male goat as a purification offering;

**17** and for the peace offering, two oxen, five rams, five male goats, and five male lambs in their first year. This was the offering of Nahshon son of Amminadab.

**18** On the second day, Nethanel son of Zuar, the leader of Issachar, brought his offering.

**19** He presented one silver dish weighing one hundred and thirty shekels, one silver basin weighing seventy shekels -- both measured by the sanctuary standard -- each filled with fine flour mixed with oil as a grain offering;

**20** one gold pan weighing ten shekels, filled with incense;

**21** one young bull, one ram, and one male lamb in its first year as a burnt offering;

**22** one male goat as a purification offering;

**23** and for the peace offering, two oxen, five rams, five male goats, and five male lambs in their first year. This was the offering of Nethanel son of Zuar.

**24** On the third day, the leader of the descendants of Zebulun -- Eliab son of Helon -- brought his offering.

**25** His offering was one silver dish weighing one hundred and thirty shekels, one silver basin weighing seventy shekels -- both measured by the sanctuary standard -- each filled with fine flour mixed with oil as a grain offering;

**26** one gold pan weighing ten shekels, filled with incense;

**27** one young bull, one ram, and one male lamb in its first year as a burnt offering;

**28** one male goat as a purification offering;

**29** and for the peace offering, two oxen, five rams, five male goats, and five male lambs in their first year. This was the offering of Eliab son of Helon.

**30** On the fourth day, the leader of the descendants of Reuben -- Elizur son of Shedeur -- brought his offering.

**31** His offering was one silver dish weighing one hundred and thirty shekels, one silver basin weighing seventy shekels -- both measured by the sanctuary standard -- each filled with fine flour mixed with oil as a grain offering;

**32** one gold pan weighing ten shekels, filled with incense;

**33** one young bull, one ram, and one male lamb in its first year as a burnt offering;

**34** one male goat as a purification offering;

**35** and for the peace offering, two oxen, five rams, five male goats, and five male lambs in their first year. This was the offering of Elizur son of Shedeur.

**36** On the fifth day, the leader of the descendants of Simeon -- Shelumiel son of Zurishaddai -- brought his offering.

**37** His offering was one silver dish weighing one hundred and thirty shekels, one silver basin weighing seventy shekels -- both measured by the sanctuary standard -- each filled with fine flour mixed with oil as a grain offering;

**38** one gold pan weighing ten shekels, filled with incense;

**39** one young bull, one ram, and one male lamb in its first year as a burnt offering;

**40** one male goat as a purification offering;

**41** and for the peace offering, two oxen, five rams, five male goats, and five male lambs in their first year. This was the offering of Shelumiel son of Zurishaddai.

**42** On the sixth day, the leader of the descendants of Gad -- Eliasaph son of Deuel -- brought his offering.

**43** His offering was one silver dish weighing one hundred and thirty shekels, one silver basin weighing seventy shekels -- both measured by the sanctuary standard -- each filled with fine flour mixed with oil as a grain offering;

**44** one gold pan weighing ten shekels, filled with incense;

**45** one young bull, one ram, and one male lamb in its first year as a burnt offering;

**46** one male goat as a purification offering;

**47** and for the peace offering, two oxen, five rams, five male goats, and five male lambs in their first year. This was the offering of Eliasaph son of Deuel.

**48** On the seventh day, the leader of the descendants of Ephraim -- Elishama son of Ammihud -- brought his offering.

**49** His offering was one silver dish weighing one hundred and thirty shekels, one silver basin weighing seventy shekels -- both measured by the sanctuary standard -- each filled with fine flour mixed with oil as a grain offering;

**50** one gold pan weighing ten shekels, filled with incense;

**51** one young bull, one ram, and one male lamb in its first year as a burnt offering;

**52** one male goat as a purification offering;

**53** and for the peace offering, two oxen, five rams, five male goats, and five male lambs in their first year. This was the offering of Elishama son of Ammihud.

**54** On the eighth day, the leader of the descendants of Manasseh -- Gamaliel son of Pedahzur -- brought his offering.

**55** His offering was one silver dish weighing one hundred and thirty shekels, one silver basin weighing seventy shekels -- both measured by the sanctuary standard -- each filled with fine flour mixed with oil as a grain offering;

**56** one gold pan weighing ten shekels, filled with incense;

**57** one young bull, one ram, and one male lamb in its first year as a burnt offering;

**58** one male goat as a purification offering;

**59** and for the peace offering, two oxen, five rams, five male goats, and five male lambs in their first year. This was the offering of Gamaliel son of Pedahzur.

**60** On the ninth day, the leader of the descendants of Benjamin -- Abidan son of Gideoni -- brought his offering.

**61** His offering was one silver dish weighing one hundred and thirty shekels, one silver basin weighing seventy shekels -- both measured by the sanctuary standard -- each filled with fine flour mixed with oil as a grain offering;

**62** one gold pan weighing ten shekels, filled with incense;

**63** one young bull, one ram, and one male lamb in its first year as a burnt offering;

**64** one male goat as a purification offering;

**65** and for the peace offering, two oxen, five rams, five male goats, and five male lambs in their first year. This was the offering of Abidan son of Gideoni.

**66** On the tenth day, the leader of the descendants of Dan -- Ahiezer son of Ammishaddai -- brought his offering.

**67** His offering was one silver dish weighing one hundred and thirty shekels, one silver basin weighing seventy shekels -- both measured by the sanctuary standard -- each filled with fine flour mixed with oil as a grain offering;

**68** one gold pan weighing ten shekels, filled with incense;

**69** one young bull, one ram, and one male lamb in its first year as a burnt offering;

**70** one male goat as a purification offering;

**71** and for the peace offering, two oxen, five rams, five male goats, and five male lambs in their first year. This was the offering of Ahiezer son of Ammishaddai.

**72** On the eleventh day, the leader of the descendants of Asher -- Pagiel son of Ochran -- brought his offering.

**73** His offering was one silver dish weighing one hundred and thirty shekels, one silver basin weighing seventy shekels -- both measured by the sanctuary standard -- each filled with fine flour mixed with oil as a grain offering;

**74** one gold pan weighing ten shekels, filled with incense;

**75** one young bull, one ram, and one male lamb in its first year as a burnt offering;

**76** one male goat as a purification offering;

**77** and for the peace offering, two oxen, five rams, five male goats, and five male lambs in their first year. This was the offering of Pagiel son of Ochran.

**78** On the twelfth day, the leader of the descendants of Naphtali -- Ahira son of Enan -- brought his offering.

**79** His offering was one silver dish weighing one hundred and thirty shekels, one silver basin weighing seventy shekels -- both measured by the sanctuary standard -- each filled with fine flour mixed with oil as a grain offering;

**80** one gold pan weighing ten shekels, filled with incense;

**81** one young bull, one ram, and one male lamb in its first year as a burnt offering;

**82** one male goat as a purification offering;

**83** and for the peace offering, two oxen, five rams, five male goats, and five male lambs in their first year. This was the offering of Ahira son of Enan.

**84** This was the total dedication offering for the altar on the day it was anointed, given by the leaders of Israel: twelve silver dishes, twelve silver basins, and twelve gold pans.

**85** Each silver dish weighed one hundred and thirty shekels, and each basin seventy -- the total silver of the vessels came to two thousand four hundred shekels by the sanctuary standard.

**86** The twelve gold pans filled with incense weighed ten shekels each by the sanctuary standard -- the total gold of the pans came to one hundred and twenty shekels.

**87** The total livestock for the burnt offering was twelve young bulls, twelve rams, and twelve male lambs in their first year, together with their grain offerings; and twelve male goats for the purification offering.

**88** The total livestock for the peace offering was twenty-four oxen, sixty rams, sixty male goats, and sixty male lambs in their first year. This was the dedication offering for the altar after it had been anointed.

**89** Whenever Moses entered the Tent of Meeting to speak with YHWH, he would hear the Voice speaking to him from above the mercy seat that rested on the Ark of the Testimony, from between the two cherubim. And the Voice spoke to him.

---
## PNEUMA's Meaning Notes

**v. 1 -- "On the day Moses finished setting up the Tabernacle"** (Heb. *be-yom kallot Mosheh le-haqim et ha-mishkan*): The Hebrew word *kallot* ("finishing") is a construct infinitive that could also be read as *kallat* ("bride of"), and the Midrash (Numbers Rabbah 12:8) exploits this phonetic overlap to portray the Tabernacle's dedication as a wedding day between YHWH and Israel. The "day" here creates a chronological tension: this refers back to the events of Exodus 40:17 (the first day of the first month of the second year), yet Numbers 1:1 places the census on the first day of the second month. The chapter thus narrates events that chronologically precede the census of chapters 1-4, illustrating the Torah's thematic rather than strictly chronological arrangement. The Leningrad Codex text is clearly legible on page 154, right column. The LXX (Vaticanus pa_0116) opens with *kai egeneto he hemera sunetelesen Mouses* -- "and it happened, the day Moses completed" -- adding the standard Septuagintal narrative marker *kai egeneto*.

**v. 2-3 -- "the leaders of Israel... the tribal chiefs who had overseen the census"** (Heb. *nesi'ei Yisrael... hem nesi'ei ha-mattot hem ha-omedim al ha-pequdim*): The text takes care to identify these leaders as the same men who supervised the census in chapter 1, connecting the administrative and the liturgical -- the men who counted the people now offer gifts on their behalf. The offering of six wagons (one per two leaders) and twelve oxen (one per leader) establishes a pattern of shared and individual responsibility. The LXX renders *nesi'ei* as *archontes* ("rulers"), a more politically loaded term that the Greek-speaking audience would immediately associate with civic leadership, collapsing the distinction between tribal and governmental authority.

**v. 5-8 -- Distribution to the Levites**: The logic of distribution is purely functional: Gershon's clan, responsible for the Tabernacle's fabrics and coverings (Num 4:24-26), received two wagons and four oxen; Merari's clan, responsible for the heavier structural components -- frames, crossbars, bases, and pillars (Num 4:31-32) -- received four wagons and eight oxen, double the allotment. The proportional distribution reflects practical need, not rank. The mention of Ithamar's oversight connects to the organizational structure established in chapter 4.

**v. 9 -- "to the descendants of Kohath he gave nothing"** (Heb. *ve-livnei Qehat lo natan*): The Kohathites carried the most sacred objects -- the Ark, the table of showbread, the lampstand, the altars, and the sacred vessels (Num 4:4-15). These could not be placed on wagons but had to be borne on human shoulders (*ba-katef yissa'u*). The insistence on shoulder-bearing is not merely practical but theological: the holiest objects demand the most intimate physical contact with their bearers, skin to pole, weight to bone. The later narrative of Uzzah's death for touching the Ark when it nearly fell from a cart (2 Sam 6:6-7) serves as a grim reminder of why wagons were inadequate for the most sacred cargo. The Vaticanus text is consistent here: *tois huiois Kaath ouk edoken* ("to the sons of Kohath he did not give").

**vv. 12-83 -- The twelve tribal offerings**: This is the longest single chapter in the Torah, and its most striking literary feature is its massive, deliberate repetition. Each of the twelve tribal leaders brings an identical offering, and the text describes each one in full, without abbreviation or shorthand. Modern editorial instinct would summarize ("each leader brought the same offering"), but the Torah refuses this efficiency. The repetition is the point. Several dimensions of meaning emerge:

**(1) Equality before YHWH.** Every tribe's offering is identical in content and weight. No tribe gives more or less. Judah, who goes first (through Nahshon, who was also the first to enter the Red Sea according to rabbinic tradition), receives no larger description than Naphtali, who goes last. The text insists on enumerating each offering in full precisely because each tribe's gift matters equally. To abbreviate would subtly imply that the later tribes' gifts were derivative or less significant.

**(2) Individual dignity within communal worship.** The twelve days of dedication space out what could have been accomplished in one day. Each tribe gets its own day -- its own moment before YHWH. This is not ceremonial inefficiency but liturgical wisdom: communal worship that erases individual identity is not true worship but mere crowd behavior. YHWH receives each offering separately, as from a distinct people with a distinct ancestor and a distinct place in the camp.

**(3) The offering contents** -- silver dish (*qa'arat kesef*), silver basin (*mizraq echad kesef*), gold pan (*kaf achat zahav*), animals for burnt, purification, and peace offerings -- represent a complete sacrificial program. The grain offering (fine flour with oil) sustains the daily service; the incense (in the gold pan) represents prayer ascending; the burnt offering (*olah*) represents total devotion; the purification offering (*chattat*) addresses sin; and the peace offering (*shelamim*) celebrates fellowship. Each tribe, in its single day, enacts the full range of Israel's relationship with God.

**v. 12 -- "Nahshon son of Amminadab, of the tribe of Judah"**: Judah leads, consistent with the marching order established in Numbers 2:3-9. Nahshon appears in Ruth 4:20 and Matthew 1:4 in the genealogy of David and ultimately of Jesus, making this first dedication offering an act that reverberates through the entire biblical narrative. The name *Nahshon* may derive from *nachash* ("serpent") or more likely from the root meaning "to divine/observe," but rabbinic tradition connects it to the sea (*nachshol*, "wave"), linking him to the Exodus crossing.

**v. 42 -- "Eliasaph son of Deuel"**: The Leningrad Codex reads *De'u'el* here, while some manuscripts and the parallel in Numbers 1:14 read *Re'u'el* ("friend of God"). The dalet/resh confusion is among the most common scribal variants in Hebrew manuscripts, as the two letters differ by only a tiny stroke. The Vaticanus LXX reads *Ragouēl* in Numbers 1:14 but *Deouēl* here, preserving the variant. The Leningrad Codex is consistent in reading *De'u'el* throughout Numbers 7.

**vv. 84-88 -- The grand totals**: After twelve iterations of the individual offerings, the text now tallies everything: twelve silver dishes (one hundred and thirty shekels each = one thousand five hundred and sixty shekels), twelve silver basins (seventy shekels each = eight hundred and forty shekels), total silver two thousand four hundred shekels; twelve gold pans (ten shekels each = one hundred and twenty shekels total); total animals for burnt offerings: twelve bulls, twelve rams, twelve lambs; total purification offerings: twelve goats; total peace offerings: twenty-four oxen, sixty rams, sixty goats, sixty lambs. The precision of the accounting reflects the priestly author's conviction that every detail of worship matters -- not a shekel is unrecorded, not an animal uncounted. The grand total also allows the reader to see the twelve individual gifts as a single, unified act of national dedication. The Leningrad Codex text on page 157 is clear in its enumeration, and the Vaticanus LXX tracks the Hebrew numbers exactly.

**v. 89 -- "he would hear the Voice speaking to him"** (Heb. *va-yishma et ha-qol middabber elav*): This final verse is one of the most theologically dense in the Torah. The hitpael form *middabber* is reflexive -- literally "speaking to itself" or "making itself heard" -- rather than the simple active *medabber* ("speaking"). The Voice does not merely speak *to* Moses; it speaks *for itself*, and Moses overhears. This grammatical nuance preserves divine transcendence: YHWH is not summoned or compelled to speak but freely communicates. The Voice comes *me-al ha-kapporet* ("from above the mercy seat") and *mi-bein shenei ha-keruvim* ("from between the two cherubim"), precisely the location promised in Exodus 25:22. The dedication offerings of the twelve tribes have prepared the sacred space; now YHWH inhabits it and speaks. This verse forms the climactic payoff of the entire chapter: the elaborate, repetitive gifts of the tribes were not empty ritual but the necessary precondition for divine communication. The Tabernacle is consecrated, the altar is dedicated, and now the God who dwells between the cherubim speaks. The Vaticanus text renders this *kai ekousen ten phonen kuriou lalountos pros auton* ("and he heard the voice of the Lord speaking to him"), replacing the reflexive Hebrew construction with a more straightforward Greek active and adding *kuriou* ("of the Lord") to identify the speaker explicitly -- a characteristic LXX clarification.

**Structural note on repetition and liturgy**: Numbers 7 is often cited as evidence of the Torah's supposedly tedious priestly style, but this judgment misunderstands the chapter's purpose. The repetition functions as liturgical text -- meant to be read aloud, chanted, or recited in a context where each tribe's name and offering would be spoken with weight and ceremony. In liturgical performance, repetition creates rhythm, solemnity, and cumulative force. Each repetition is not redundant but additive: by the twelfth recitation, the hearer has internalized the offering formula so deeply that it becomes a kind of incantation, a verbal equivalent of the twelve stones at Gilgal (Josh 4) or the twelve gates of the New Jerusalem (Rev 21). The chapter moves from the practical (wagons for the Levites, vv. 1-9) through the ceremonial (twelve days of identical offerings, vv. 10-83) to the transcendent (the Voice from between the cherubim, v. 89). The trajectory is from earth to heaven, from human gift to divine speech -- and the repetition is the bridge, the slow, deliberate accumulation of human devotion that finally opens the space for God's voice. The Leningrad Codex preserves this chapter across four full manuscript pages (pp. 154-157), and the Vaticanus across three pages (pa_0116-0118), both witnesses testifying to the chapter's completeness and integrity in the textual tradition.
